{"title_page": "Third-party and independent candidates for the 2020 United States presidential election", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = Third-party and independent candidates for the<br />2020 U.S. presidential election\n| country = United States\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = yes\n| previous_election = Third-party and independent candidates for the 2016 United States presidential election\n| previous_year = 2016\n| next_election = Third-party and independent candidates for the 2024 United States presidential election \n| next_year = 2024\n}}\n{{US 2020 presidential elections series}}\n\nThe following political parties, and [[Independent politician|independent candidate]]s, currently have [[ballot access]] to fewer than 270 [[United States Electoral College|electoral votes]]. These parties and/or their nominees will need to conduct ballot access drives (or run [[Write-in candidate|write-in]] campaigns) in order to have a theoretical chance of winning the election. Ballot access deadlines vary from state to state, with the latest deadlines falling in September 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Winger |first1=Richard |authorlink1=Richard Winger |title=2020 Petitioning for President |url=http://ballot-access.org/2019/08/25/august-2019-ballot-access-news-print-edition/ |website=[[Ballot Access News]] |accessdate=September 30, 2019 |date=August 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Declared candidates==\n{{legend|bisque|Seeking party's nomination}}\n<!-- Parties and candidates in this section have attained ballot lines in one or more states (or expected), but not for a majority of electoral votes. Individuals included in this section have either received the presidential nomination of a [[minor party]], or are running as an [[Independent politician|independent]] presidential candidate. -->\n<!-- Please list only minor parties which have a standalone page on Wikipedia. -->\n<!-- Please provide at least ONE (1) reliable SECONDARY source per candidate before adding candidate(s) to this section. See [[Wikipedia:Identifying reliable sources]] for guidelines on sourcing. -->\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!style=\"width:15em;\"|Party\n!style=\"width:12em;\"|Presidential nominee\n!style=\"width:12em;\"|Vice presidential nominee\n!style=\"width:5em;\" data-sort-type=\"number\"|Attainable Electors<br />(''write-in'')\n!style=\"width:18em;\"|States with ballot access<br />(''write-in'')\n!style=\"width:2em;\"|Ref.\n|-\n|-style=\"background:bisque;\"\n|Alliance Party\n|[[File:Rocky_De_La_Fuente1_(2)_(cropped).jpg|150x150px]]<br>'''[[Rocky De La Fuente]]'''<br>Businessman and perennial candidate from [[Florida]]\n|[[File:LG PICs 2 002.JPG|150x150px]]<br>'''[[Darcy Richardson]]'''<br> Author, historian and political activist from [[Florida]]\n|9\n|South Carolina\n|<ref name=Darcy/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ballot-access.org/2020/04/09/alliance-party-will-choose-presidential-nominee-on-april-25-saturday/#comment-761411|title=South Carolina is already on.|website=Ballot Access News|last1=[[Richard Winger|Winger]]|first1=[[Richard Winger|Richard]]|date=April 9, 2020|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[American Solidarity Party]]\n|[[File:Brian T. Carroll - head shot .75 aspect ratio.png|150x150px]]<br />'''[[Brian T. Carroll|Brian Carroll]]'''<br />Educator from [[California]]\n|[[File:Amar_Right_Clean.jpg|150x150px]]<br />'''Amar Patel'''<br />Chairman of the ASP from [[Illinois]]\n|''(53)''\n|''(Alabama, Iowa, New Hampshire, New Jersey, Oregon,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sos.oregon.gov/elections/Documents/elec_law_summary.pdf|page=14|title=Election Law Summary|publisher=Elections Division|website=Oregon Secretary of State|access-date=2016-10-19|quote=Oregon voters have the option of not voting for any of the candidates for office who are printed on the ballot, but instead writing in a name of a candidate for each office. All write-in votes for each office on the ballot are tallied together with a lump sum recorded unless:  1 No names of candidates are printed on the ballot for the office; or 2 If the total number of write-in votes for candidates equals or exceeds the total number of votes for any candidate for the same nomination or office.  In these two circumstances, the county clerk tallies all write-in votes cast for the office to show the total number of votes for each write-in candidate.}}</ref> Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont<ref name=\"write-in\">{{cite web |url=http://ballotpedia.org/Ballot_access_for_presidential_candidates#Requirements_for_write-in_candidates|title=Ballot access for presidential candidates|website=Ballotpedia|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref>)''\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docquery.fec.gov/pdf/605/201910019163579605/201910019163579605.pdf|title=FEC Form 2|website=FEC.gov}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Carroll |first1=Brian |title=April 5, 2019 Preview |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WnZb2naU92Y |website=YouTube |accessdate=April 15, 2019 |date=April 2, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Bread and Roses (political party)|Bread and Roses]]\n|'''[[Jerome Segal]]'''<br>Philosopher from [[Maryland]]\n|TBA\n|10\n|Maryland\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/jerome-segal-of-maryland-socialist-bread-and-roses-party-to-run-for-president/2019/08/28/26a02ce8-c8f7-11e9-a4f3-c081a126de70_story.html?arc404=true|title=Jerome Segal, of Maryland socialist Bread and Roses party, to run for president|date=August 28, 2019|first=Rachel|last=Chason|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=September 3, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|-style=\"background:bisque;\"\n|[[Constitution Party of the United States|Constitution Party]]\n|[[File:Don_Blankenship_Image_(cropped).jpeg|150x150px]]<br>'''[[Don Blankenship]]'''<br>Coal executive from [[West Virginia]]\n|TBA\n|141\n|Arkansas, Colorado, Florida, Hawaii, Michigan, Mississippi, Missouri, New Mexico, Nevada, North Carolina, Oregon, South Carolina, Utah, Wisc