olitics/2019/10/21/andrew-yang-rules-out-third-party-or-independent-run-if-hes-not-democratic-nominee/|title=Andrew Yang rules out minor party or independent run if he's not the Democratic nominee|author=Amy B. Wang|date=Oct 21, 2019|website=The Washington Post}}</ref> (''ran for [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|Democratic]] nomination'') (''endorsed [[Joe Biden|Biden]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/10/politics/andrew-yang-endorses-joe-biden/index.html|title=Andrew Yang endorses Joe Biden for president|website=CNN|last1=LeBlanc|first1=Paul|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 Republican Party presidential primaries#Candidates|2020 Republican Party presidential candidates]]\n* [[2020 Democratic Party presidential candidates]]\n* [[2020 Libertarian Party presidential primaries#Candidates|2020 Libertarian Party presidential candidates]]\n* [[2020 Green Party presidential primaries#Candidates|2020 Green Party presidential candidates]]\n* [[2020 Constitution Party presidential primaries#Candidates|2020 Constitution Party presidential candidates]]\n* [[Timeline of the 2020 United States presidential election]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=}}\n\n{{United States presidential election, 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:United States third party and independent presidential candidates, 2020}}\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2020 United States presidential election| ]]\n[[Category:Independent politicians in the United States|2020 presidential candidates]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = Third-party and independent candidates for the<br />2020 U.S. presidential election\n| country = United States\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = yes\n| previous_election = Third-party and independent candidates for the 2016 United States presidential election\n| previous_year = 2016\n| next_election = Third-party and independent candidates for the 2024 United States presidential election \n| next_year = 2024\n}}\n{{US 2020 presidential elections series}}\n\nThe following political parties, and [[Independent politician|independent candidate]]s, currently have [[ballot access]] to fewer than 270 [[United States Electoral College|electoral votes]]. These parties and/or their nominees will need to conduct ballot access drives (or run [[Write-in candidate|write-in]] campaigns) in order to have a theoretical chance of winning the election. Ballot access deadlines vary from state to state, with the latest deadlines falling in September 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Winger |first1=Richard |authorlink1=Richard Winger |title=2020 Petitioning for President |url=http://ballot-access.org/2019/08/25/august-2019-ballot-access-news-print-edition/ |website=[[Ballot Access News]] |accessdate=September 30, 2019 |date=August 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Declared candidates==\n{{legend|bisque|Seeking party's nomination}}\n<!-- Parties and candidates in this section have attained ballot lines in one or more states (or expected), but not for a majority of electoral votes. Individuals included in this section have either received the presidential nomination of a [[minor party]], or are running as an [[Independent politician|independent]] presidential candidate. -->\n<!-- Please list only minor parties which have a standalone page on Wikipedia. -->\n<!-- Please provide at least ONE (1) reliable SECONDARY source per candidate before adding candidate(s) to this section. See [[Wikipedia:Identifying reliable sources]] for guidelines on sourcing. -->\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!style=\"width:15em;\"|Party\n!style=\"width:12em;\"|Presidential nominee\n!style=\"width:12em;\"|Vice presidential nominee\n!style=\"width:5em;\" data-sort-type=\"number\"|Attainable Electors<br />(''write-in'')\n!style=\"width:18em;\"|States with ballot access<br />(''write-in'')\n!style=\"width:2em;\"|Ref.\n|-\n|-style=\"background:bisque;\"\n