{"title_page": "Emmerich K\u00e1lm\u00e1n", "text_new": "{{Eastern name order|K\u00e1lm\u00e1n Imre}}\n{{Inline|date=January 2018}}\n'''Emmerich K\u00e1lm\u00e1n''' ({{lang-hu|K\u00e1lm\u00e1n Imre}}; 24 October 1882 \u2013 30 October 1953) was an [[Austria-Hungary|Hungarian]] composer of [[operetta]]s and a prominent figure in the development of [[Operetta#Austria\u2013Hungary|Viennese operetta]] in the 20th century. Among his most popular works are ''[[Die Cs\u00e1rd\u00e1sf\u00fcrstin]]'' (1915) and ''[[Countess Maritza|Gr\u00e4fin Mariza]]'' (1924). Influences on his compositional style include Hungarian folk music (such as the [[cs\u00e1rd\u00e1s]]), the Viennese style of precursors such as [[Johann Strauss II]] and [[Franz Leh\u00e1r]], and, in his later works, American [[jazz]].  As a result of the ''[[Anschluss]],'' K\u00e1lm\u00e1n and his family fled to Paris and then to the United States. He eventually returned to Europe in and died in Paris in 1953.\n\n==Biography==\n{{onesource|section|date=January 2018}}\nK\u00e1lm\u00e1n was born '''Imre Koppstein''' in [[Si\u00f3fok]], then in [[Austria-Hungary]], on the southern shore of [[Lake Balaton]], to a [[Jew]]ish family. K\u00e1lm\u00e1n initially intended to become a concert [[piano|pianist]], but because of early-onset [[arthritis]], he focused on composition instead. He studied [[music theory]] and [[musical composition|composition]] at the [[Franz Liszt Academy of Music|National Hungarian Royal Academy of Music]] (then the Budapest Academy of Music), where he was a fellow student of [[B\u00e9la Bart\u00f3k]] and [[Zolt\u00e1n Kod\u00e1ly]] under [[Hans von Koessler|Hans K\u00f6ssler]]. \n\nHis early symphonic poems ''Saturnalia'' and ''Endre es Johanna'' were well-received, although he failed to achieve publication. He also composed piano music and wrote many songs: a song cycle on poems by Ludwig Jacobowski and a song collection published under the title ''Dalai''.\n[[File:M.Sander - Imre Kalman, 2015.jpg|thumb|upright|Young K\u00e1lm\u00e1n, by [[Mart Sander]]]]\nHowever, the popularity of his humorous cabaret songs led him towards the composition of [[operetta]]s. His first great success was ''Tat\u00e1rj\u00e1r\u00e1s'' \u2013 ''Ein Herbstman\u00f6ver'' in German, meaning ''Autumn maneuver'', although the English title is ''[[The Gay Hussars]]'', which was first staged at the {{Lang|de|Lustspieltheater}} in [[Budapest]], on 22 February 1908. Thereafter he moved to [[Vienna]], where he achieved worldwide fame through his operettas ''[[Der Zigeunerprimas]]'', ''[[Die Cs\u00e1rd\u00e1sf\u00fcrstin]]'', ''[[Gr\u00e4fin Mariza]]'', and ''[[Die Zirkusprinzessin]]''.\n[[File:Kalman Imre B Siofok.jpg|thumb|upright|Bust of K\u00e1lm\u00e1n in Si\u00f3fok]]\nK\u00e1lm\u00e1n and [[Franz Leh\u00e1r]] were the leading composers of what has been called the \"Silver Age\" of Viennese operetta during the first quarter of the 20th century. He became well known for his fusion of Viennese [[waltz]] with Hungarian [[cs\u00e1rd\u00e1s]]. Even so, [[Polyphony|polyphonically]] and [[Melody|melodically]], K\u00e1lm\u00e1n was a devoted follower of [[Giacomo Puccini]], while in his [[orchestration]] methods he employed principles characteristic of [[Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky|Tchaikovsky]]'s music.\n\nDespite his Jewish origins he was one of [[Adolf Hitler]]'s favorite composers. After the [[Anschluss]], he rejected Hitler's offer to become an '[[honorary Aryan]]' and was forced to move first to Paris, then to the United States, settling in California in 1940.<ref>[http://www.lyricoperasandiego.org/resource_library/PeopleKalman.htm Lyric Opera San Diego] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720120328/http://www.lyricoperasandiego.org/resource_library/PeopleKalman.htm|date=20 July 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Last years and death==\nFollowing his emigration, performances of his works were prohibited in Nazi Germany. He emigrated back to Vienna from New York in 1949 before moving in 1951 to Paris, where he died.{{cn|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Popular culture==\nIn 1958 a West German biopic ''[[The Csardas King]]'' was made of his life, starring [[Gerhard Riedmann]] in the lead role.\n\n==Operettas==\n* ''Tat\u00e1rj\u00e1r\u00e1s'' (The Mongol Invasion) \u2013 Budapest, 1908\n** ''Ein Herbstman\u00f6ver'' \u2013 Vienna, 1909 (German version of ''Tat\u00e1rj\u00e1r\u00e1s'')\n** ''[[The Gay Hussars]]''  \u2013 New York, 1909 (American version of ''Tat\u00e1rj\u00e1r\u00e1s'')<ref>{{Ibdb title|6811|The Gay Hussars}}</ref>\n** ''Autumn Manoeuvres'' \u2013 London, 1912 (English version of ''Tat\u00e1rj\u00e1r\u00e1s'')\n* ''[[Az obsitos]]'' (The Veteran) \u2013 Budapest, 1910\n** ''Der gute Kamerad'' \u2013 Vienna, 1911 (German revision of ''Az Obsitos'')\n** ''Gold gab ich f\u00fcr Eisen'' \u2013 Vienna, 1914 (revision of ''Der gute Kamerad'')\n** ''Her Soldier Boy'' \u2013 New York, 1916<ref>{{Ibdb title|7767|Her Soldier Boy}}</ref>\n** ''Soldier Boy'' \u2013 London, 1918\n* ''[[Der Zigeunerprimas]]'' (The Gypsy Band Leader) \u2013 Vienna, 1912\n** ''Sari'' \u2013 New York, 1914<ref>{{Ibdb title|7028|Sari}}</ref>\n* ''The Blue House'' \u2013 London, 1912\n* ''Der kleine K\u00f6nig'' (The Little King) \u2013 Vienna, 1912\n* ''[[Zsuzsi kisasszony]]'' \u2013 Budapest, 1915\n** ''Miss Springtime'' \u2013 New York, 1916<ref>{{Ibdb title|8446|Miss Springtime}}</ref>\n** ''Die Faschingsfee'' \u2013 Vienna, 1917 (German revision of ''Zsuzsi kisasszony'')\n* ''[[Die Cs\u00e1rd\u00e1sf\u00fcrstin]]'' \u2013 Vienna, 1915\n** ''The Riviera Girl'' \u2013 New York, 1917<ref>{{Ibdb title|8578|The Riviera Girl}}</ref>\n** ''The Gipsy Princess'' \u2013 London, 1921\n* ''Das Hollandweibchen'' \u2013 Vienna, 1920\n** ''A Little Dutch Girl'' \u2013 London, 1920\n** ''La Holandesita'' \u2013 Spain, 1921 (Spanish version by Casimiro Giralt)\n** ''The Dutch Girl'' \u2013 U.S., 1925\n* ''[[Die Bajadere (operetta)|Die Bajadere]]'' \u2013 Vienna, 1921\n** ''The Yankee Princess'' \u2013 New York, 1922<ref>{{Ibdb title|9125|The Yankee Princess}}</ref>\n* ''[[Gr\u00e4fin Mariza]]'' \u2013 Vienna, 1924\n** ''Countess Maritza'' \u2013 New York, 1926<ref>{{Ibdb title|10120|Countess Maritza}}</ref>\n** ''Maritza'' \u2013 London, 1938\n* ''[[Die Zirkusprinzessin]]'' \u2013 Vienna, 1926\n** ''The Circus Princess'' \u2013 New York, 1927<ref>{{Ibdb title|10293|The Circus Princess}}</ref>\n* ''[[Golden Dawn (operetta)|Golden Dawn]]'' \u2013 New York, 1927<ref>{{Ibdb title|10507|Golden Dawn}}</ref>\n* ''[[Die Herzogin von Chicago]]'' \u2013 Vienna, 1928\n** ''The Duchess of Chicago'' \u2013 U.S., 1929\n* ''[[Das Veilchen vom Montmartre]]'' \u2013 Vienna, 1930\n** ''Paris in Spring'' \u2013 U.S., 1930\n** ''A Kiss in Spring'' \u2013 London, 1932\n* ''Der Teufelsreiter'' (Az \u00f6rd\u00f6glovas \u2013 The Devil Rider) \u2013 Vienna, 1932\n* ''[[Kaiserin Josephine]]'' \u2013 Zurich, 1936\n* ''Miss Underground'' \u2013 written 1942, unproduced\n* ''[[Marinka (operetta)|Marinka]]'' \u2013 New York, 1945<ref>{{Ibdb title|1717|Marinka}}</ref>\n* ''[[Arizona Lady]]'' \u2013 Bern, 1954\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n* Clarke, Kevin. ''Im Himmel spielt auch schon die Jazzband. Emmerich K\u00e1lm\u00e1n und die transatlantische Operette 1928\u20131932''. Hamburg: von Bockel Verlag, 2007 (examines K\u00e1lm\u00e1n's jazz-operettas of the 1920s, with extensive English quotes from historical Broadway- and West End reviews)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160303230357/http://etd.lsu.edu/docs/available/etd-06142005-160600/unrestricted/Martin_thesis.pdf Article on the operettas of K\u00e1lm\u00e1n]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110727152132/http://operetta-research-center.org/main.php?task=searchart&tab=2&id=00084 Historical reviews and a biography/worklist] by [[Kurt G\u00e4nzl]])\n\n== Further reading ==\n* [[Yuri Nagibin|Nagibin, Yuri]]. \u0412\u0435\u0447\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430. Russia, ACT, 2004. {{ISBN|5-17-021655-6}}. (pp.&nbsp;201\u2013345)\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Emmerich K\u00e1lm\u00e1n}}\n*{{IMSLP|id=K\u00e1lm\u00e1n, Emmerich|cname=Emmerich K\u00e1lm\u00e1n}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090106185206/http://www.operettafoundation.org/oarchives.htm Links to numerous K\u00e1lm\u00e1n recordings]\n*{{IMDb name|0477578|Emmerich K\u00e1lm\u00e1n}}\n*<!--https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QjTI7M-PbOI-->\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Opera}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kalman, Emmerich}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1953 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Si\u00f3fok]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Jews]]\n[[Category:Jewish classical composers]]\n[[Category:Hungarian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Hungarian musical theatre composers]]\n[[Category:Hungarian opera composers]]\n[[Category:Male opera composers]]\n[[Category:Jewish opera composers]]\n[[Category:American people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Franz Liszt Academy of Music alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Eastern name order|K\u00e1lm\u00e1n Imre}}\n{{Inline|date=January 2018}}\n'''Emmerich K\u00e1lm\u00e1n''' (24 October 1882 \u2013 30 October 1953) was a Hungarian [[composer]] of [[operetta]]s.\n\n==Biography==\n{{onesource|section|date=January 2018}}\nK\u00e1lm\u00e1n was born '''Imre Koppstein''' in [[Si\u00f3fok]], then in [[Austria-Hungary]], on the southern shore of [[Lake Balaton]], to a [[Jew]]ish family. K\u00e1lm\u00e1n initially intended to become a concert [[piano|pianist]], but because of early-onset [[arthritis]], he focused on composition instead. He studied [[music theory]] and [[musical composition|composition]] at the [[Franz Liszt Academy of Music|National Hungarian Royal Academy of Music]] (then the Budapest Academy of Music), where he was a fellow student of [[B\u00e9la Bart\u00f3k]] and [[Zolt\u00e1n Kod\u00e1ly]] under [[Hans von Koessler|Hans K\u00f6ssler]]. \n\nHis early symphonic poems ''Saturnalia'' and ''Endre es Johanna'' were well-received, although he failed to achieve publication. He also composed piano music and wrote many songs: a song cycle on poems by Ludwig Jacobowski and a song collection published under the title ''Dalai''.\n[[File:M.Sander - Imre Kalman, 2015.jpg|thumb|upright|Young K\u00e1lm\u00e1n, by [[Mart Sander]]]]\nHowever, the popularity of his humorous cabaret songs led him towards the composition of [[operetta]]s. His first great success was ''Tat\u00e1rj\u00e1r\u00e1s'' \u2013 ''Ein Herbstman\u00f6ver'' in German, meaning ''Autumn maneuver'', although the English title is ''[[The Gay Hussars]]'', which was first staged at the {{Lang|de|Lustspieltheater}} in [[Budapest]], on 22 February 1908. Thereafter he moved to [[Vienna]], where he achieved worldwide fame through his operettas ''[[Der Zigeunerprimas]]'', ''[[Die Cs\u00e1rd\u00e1sf\u00fcrstin]]'', ''[[Gr\u00e4fin Mariza]]'', and ''[[Die Zirkusprinzessin]]''.\n[[File:Kalman Imre B Siofok.jpg|thumb|upright|Bust of K\u00e1lm\u00e1n in Si\u00f3fok]]\nK\u00e1lm\u00e1n and [[Franz Leh\u00e1r]] were the leading composers of what has been called the \"Silver Age\" of Viennese operetta during the first quarter of the 20th century. He became well known for his fusion of Viennese [[waltz]] with Hungarian [[cs\u00e1rd\u00e1s]]. Even so, [[Polyphony|polyphonically]] and [[Melody|melodically]], K\u00e1lm\u00e1n was a devoted follower of [[Giacomo Puccini]], while in his [[orchestration]] methods he employed principles characteristic of [[Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky|Tchaikovsky]]'s music.\n\nDespite his Jewish origins he was one of [[Adolf Hitler]]'s favorite composers. After the [[Anschluss]], he rejected Hitler's offer to become an '[[honorary Aryan]]' and was forced to move first to Paris, then to the United States, settling in California in 1940.<ref>[http://www.lyricoperasandiego.org/resource_library/PeopleKalman.htm Lyric Opera San Diego] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720120328/http://www.lyricoperasandiego.org/resource_library/PeopleKalman.htm|date=20 July 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Last years and death==\nFollowing his emigration, performances of his works were prohibited in Nazi Germany. He emigrated back to Vienna from New York in 1949 before moving in 1951 to Paris, where he died.{{cn|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Popular culture==\nIn 1958 a West German biopic ''[[The Csardas King]]'' was made of his life, starring [[Gerhard Riedmann]] in the lead role.\n\n==Operettas==\n* ''Tat\u00e1rj\u00e1r\u00e1s'' (The Mongol Invasion) \u2013 Budapest, 1908\n** ''Ein Herbstman\u00f6ver'' \u2013 Vienna, 1909 (German version of ''Tat\u00e1rj\u00e1r\u00e1s'')\n** ''[[The Gay Hussars]]''  \u2013 New York, 1909 (American version of ''Tat\u00e1rj\u00e1r\u00e1s'')<ref>{{Ibdb title|6811|The Gay Hussars}}</ref>\n** ''Autumn Manoeuvres'' \u2013 London, 1912 (English version of ''Tat\u00e1rj\u00e1r\u00e1s'')\n* ''[[Az obsitos]]'' (The Veteran) \u2013 Budapest, 1910\n** ''Der gute Kamerad'' \u2013 Vienna, 1911 (German revision of ''Az Obsitos'')\n** ''Gold gab ich f\u00fcr Eisen'' \u2013 Vienna, 1914 (revision of ''Der gute Kamerad'')\n** ''Her Soldier Boy'' \u2013 New York, 1916<ref>{{Ibdb title|7767|Her Soldier Boy}}</ref>\n** ''Soldier Boy'' \u2013 London, 1918\n* ''[[Der Zigeunerprimas]]'' (The Gypsy Band Leader) \u2013 Vienna, 1912\n** ''Sari'' \u2013 New York, 1914<ref>{{Ibdb title|7028|Sari}}</ref>\n* ''The Blue House'' \u2013 London, 1912\n* ''Der kleine K\u00f6nig'' (The Little King) \u2013 Vienna, 1912\n* ''[[Zsuzsi kisasszony]]'' \u2013 Budapest, 1915\n** ''Miss Springtime'' \u2013 New York, 1916<ref>{{Ibdb title|8446|Miss Springtime}}</ref>\n** ''Die Faschingsfee'' \u2013 Vienna, 1917 (German revision of ''Zsuzsi kisasszony'')\n* ''[[Die Cs\u00e1rd\u00e1sf\u00fcrstin]]'' \u2013 Vienna, 1915\n** ''The Riviera Girl'' \u2013 New York, 1917<ref>{{Ibdb title|8578|The Riviera Girl}}</ref>\n** ''The Gipsy Princess'' \u2013 London, 1921\n* ''Das Hollandweibchen'' \u2013 Vienna, 1920\n** ''A Little Dutch Girl'' \u2013 London, 1920\n** ''La Holandesita'' \u2013 Spain, 1921 (Spanish version by Casimiro Giralt)\n** ''The Dutch Girl'' \u2013 U.S., 1925\n* ''[[Die Bajadere (operetta)|Die Bajadere]]'' \u2013 Vienna, 1921\n** ''The Yankee Princess'' \u2013 New York, 1922<ref>{{Ibdb title|9125|The Yankee Princess}}</ref>\n* ''[[Gr\u00e4fin Mariza]]'' \u2013 Vienna, 1924\n** ''Countess Maritza'' \u2013 New York, 1926<ref>{{Ibdb title|10120|Countess Maritza}}</ref>\n** ''Maritza'' \u2013 London, 1938\n* ''[[Die Zirkusprinzessin]]'' \u2013 Vienna, 1926\n** ''The Circus Princess'' \u2013 New York, 1927<ref>{{Ibdb title|10293|The Circus Princess}}</ref>\n* ''[[Golden Dawn (operetta)|Golden Dawn]]'' \u2013 New York, 1927<ref>{{Ibdb title|10507|Golden Dawn}}</ref>\n* ''[[Die Herzogin von Chicago]]'' \u2013 Vienna, 1928\n** ''The Duchess of Chicago'' \u2013 U.S., 1929\n* ''[[Das Veilchen vom Montmartre]]'' \u2013 Vienna, 1930\n** ''Paris in Spring'' \u2013 U.S., 1930\n** ''A Kiss in Spring'' \u2013 London, 1932\n* ''Der Teufelsreiter'' (Az \u00f6rd\u00f6glovas \u2013 The Devil Rider) \u2013 Vienna, 1932\n* ''[[Kaiserin Josephine]]'' \u2013 Zurich, 1936\n* ''Miss Underground'' \u2013 written 1942, unproduced\n* ''[[Marinka (operetta)|Marinka]]'' \u2013 New York, 1945<ref>{{Ibdb title|1717|Marinka}}</ref>\n* ''[[Arizona Lady]]'' \u2013 Bern, 1954\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n* Clarke, Kevin. ''Im Himmel spielt auch schon die Jazzband. Emmerich K\u00e1lm\u00e1n und die transatlantische Operette 1928\u20131932''. Hamburg: von Bockel Verlag, 2007 (examines K\u00e1lm\u00e1n's jazz-operettas of the 1920s, with extensive English quotes from historical Broadway- and West End reviews)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160303230357/http://etd.lsu.edu/docs/available/etd-06142005-160600/unrestricted/Martin_thesis.pdf Article on the operettas of K\u00e1lm\u00e1n]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110727152132/http://operetta-research-center.org/main.php?task=searchart&tab=2&id=00084 Historical reviews and a biography/worklist] by [[Kurt G\u00e4nzl]])\n\n== Further reading ==\n* [[Yuri Nagibin|Nagibin, Yuri]]. \u0412\u0435\u0447\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430. Russia, ACT, 2004. {{ISBN|5-17-021655-6}}. (pp.&nbsp;201\u2013345)\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Emmerich K\u00e1lm\u00e1n}}\n*{{IMSLP|id=K\u00e1lm\u00e1n, Emmerich|cname=Emmerich K\u00e1lm\u00e1n}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090106185206/http://www.operettafoundation.org/oarchives.htm Links to numerous K\u00e1lm\u00e1n recordings]\n*{{IMDb name|0477578|Emmerich K\u00e1lm\u00e1n}}\n*<!--https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QjTI7M-PbOI-->\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Opera}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kalman, Emmerich}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1953 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Si\u00f3fok]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Jews]]\n[[Category:Jewish classical composers]]\n[[Category:Hungarian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Hungarian musical theatre composers]]\n[[Category:Hungarian opera composers]]\n[[Category:Male opera composers]]\n[[Category:Jewish opera composers]]\n[[Category:American people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Franz Liszt Academy of Music alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Mosaic78", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emmerich_K%C3%A1lm%C3%A1n"}
